<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is dew point?", answer: "The temperature at which water vapor in the air starts to condense. If the dew point is 60 °F and the air cools to 60 °F, water droplets form on cold surfaces — car windows, basement walls, cold water pipes. Dew point is a better humidity indicator than relative humidity because it does not change with temperature. A dew point below 55 °F feels dry, 55-65 °F feels comfortable, and above 70 °F feels oppressive." },
  { question: "What is wet bulb temperature?", answer: "The lowest temperature air can be cooled to by evaporating water into it. Wet bulb is always below or equal to dry bulb. It matters for evaporative cooling, heat stress assessment, and cooling tower design. A wet bulb above 80 °F starts to cause heat illness in healthy adults; above 88 °F, even with fans and shade, the human body cannot shed heat fast enough and death becomes likely within hours." },
  { question: "What is humidity ratio?", answer: "The mass of water vapor per unit mass of dry air, usually expressed as kg of water per kg of dry air (or grains of water per pound in imperial units; 7,000 grains = 1 pound). Humidity ratio stays constant as long as no water is added or removed — unlike relative humidity, which changes with temperature. HVAC engineers use humidity ratio to track moisture through air handling processes." },
  { question: "What is enthalpy and why does it matter for HVAC?", answer: "Enthalpy is the total energy of air (sensible heat + latent heat from water vapor) per unit mass. It is used to calculate cooling loads and size cooling coils. When an HVAC system cools air from 90 °F/50% RH (36 BTU/lb) to 55 °F/95% RH (23 BTU/lb), it must remove the enthalpy difference (13 BTU/lb) from every pound of air flowing through. Multiply by the mass flow rate (cfm × 4.5) to get the cooling capacity." },
  { question: "How accurate is the Stull wet-bulb approximation?", answer: "The Stull (2011) formula is accurate to within about ±1 °F for typical indoor and outdoor conditions (0-50 °C dry bulb, 5-99% RH). It is not accurate at very low humidity or temperatures near freezing. For critical applications (commissioning, research), use iterative psychrometric software that solves the exact enthalpy-balance equation." }
]) %>

